				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Sony IT dept. owes me a mask<a name="57119"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 17 04 12:39 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well, here's the thing -- as I see it, you can start dictating to the guild that certain items will be reserved for certain classes until all of that class have them, but how far do you carry it?  My guild DOES have a policy that the first 4 Blades of War off RZtW go to warriors.  But that's the only item we have restricted in that way.  If we say that the Hydrotha mask is bards-first, then what about piercers with backstab mods?  And if we go that far, what about focus effects that clearly favor certain classes or types of classes?  What about an item like the Valiant Belt of Fallen Heroes off Mith Marr?  That belt is all/all and for most of the casters in my guild, it would be more mana in one item than anything else they own.  But the belt has 41% haste.  Is the haste for a melee more important than 125 hp/mana and 12 INT for a wizard?  Probably, but is it enough that it is in the best interests of a guild to restrict looting and annoy people?
<br />

<br />
Bottom line: +3 mana regen and 150 HP/125 mana is a HUGE benefit to all hybrids.  Yes, having a singing mod in a non-weapon slot is vastly more significant to bards, but is that impact on a single bard worth a guild alienating members by restricting the item?  Very tough call.  Personally, I am in favor of using the class-restrict button on our loot policy as seldom as we possibly can.  In this case, it probably means I will never get that mask.  Such is life.</span></td>
